data.name: rtb_tAbout.Text
data.value:
PatchMaster was designed to automate the process of detecting and deploying Microsoft Patches to devices being managed by ConfigMgr. This tool was not designed to compete or replace ADR’s, which can be used for the job adequately, with some tolerable-for-some shortfalls compared to PatchMaster.
To help get you on your way:
· Setup ConfigMgr, WSUS and your SUP, make sure your first synchronisation is successful and patches show in ConfigMgr, create Device Collections and Security Scopes to be used for SUM
· Understand and master the Configure tab, all Device Groups have a corresponding Deployment Setting, customise away, the naming bar has been tested using the following combinations:
Textbox, Year, Month, Product, Classification (SUM - 2018 - August - Product - Classification) Textbox, Year, Month, Product, (SUM - 2018 - August - Product)
· Create Rules to define patches that are to be deployed, use the Include filter to remove unwanted patches, and use the Exclude filter to narrow the resulting patch list down further
Do not create multiple Rules that reference both the same Products and Classifications, keep it distinct, break down a Product by Classification into individual Rules if needed
· Create deployments and associate them with Device Groups, recommend to use Hard Test, Pilot and Live and stagger across 8 days, time offset is HH:MM:SS format
· Create Security Scopes and associate them with Device Groups, Reporting SUG's can be separated from Deployment SUG's, two entries per Device Group (Deployment, Reporting), same Security Scope for both works if desired
· Use Check for Patches to see the results of your Rules, there is a patch metadata caching system (2hr life time) so if there has been a change in patch metadata in ConfigMgr, PatchMaster will need to be forced to rescan ConfigMgr, this usually only happens if SUG’s and SUP’s are deleted while PatchMaster is running or a WSUS synchronisation has taken place during the lifetime of the cache, if the cache expires it is marked for refresh at the next check for patches
· Use Refresh SUGs when there has been a change to the SUGs on the site server, such as SUG's being deleted without PatchMaster being restarted
· Choose to run the SUM Clean-up feature at the end of a build, which removes all superseded patches from ALL SUG's and SUP's
· Select Patches (right-click) that are not desired and put them on an ignore list, easily return them from the Ignore Patches tab
· Select Build to build out any patches found by PatchMaster, during this process the Logs tab and the log file will indicate progress, a flight check is performed to make sure each device group is sound for use, and if SUM maintenance is selected it will be run after the build out has completed
· Once PatchMaster is configured and tested, put the word SILENT after the command (PatchMaster.exe SILENT) and PatchMaster will begin a build out automatically if any patches are found, ideal for scheduling checks and build outs using a Windows scheduled task
· PatchMaster will reuse already downloaded content, making it easy to run PatchMaster across multiple Hierarchies by copying the content and pointing PatchMaster at the site server (click the … when starting up to select a new Site server)
· Failure to download patches will result in the SUG and SUP being removed, the files will remain and can be reused by PatchMaster if hashed successfully when a build is tried again
· The Log tab is your friend, it'll mostly automatically show when PatchMaster is doing something, there is also a log in the folder PatchMaster is run from
Refer to the TechNet Gallery for further information on the tool
